Nam et urgemur a commu, nione naturalis disciplinae converti ad proprietatem Christianae totam jam defendendam per ceteras Ι quoque species coronarum, quae aliis usibus pro- spectae videntur, ut aliis substantiis structae, ne, quia non ex floribus constant, quorum usum natura sig- navit, ut ipsa haec laurea militaris, non credantur admittere sectae interdictionem, quia evaserint na- turae praescriptionem. Video igitur et curiosius et plenius agendum ab originibus usque ad profectus et excessus rei. Litterae ad hoc saeculares necessariae. De suis enim instrumentis saecularia probari necesse est. ⁴ de proximo. All MSS. except Cod. Ag. proximo. Cod. Ag. de prom-ime, whence Rig. and Oehl. de proximo. This is confirmed by De Speet. c. 2, quoted above.

⁵ nostro privatim capiti, ‘to the head of us Christians peculiarly.’ For the constr. of interdicunt, see De Idol. c. 4, n. 2.

⁶ Proinde-..interdicunt. ‘There- fore let these crown-lovers own meanwhile, as men, the authority of nature by reason of common wis- dom, and as the nearest worshippers of the God of nature, let them own

the assurances of their own religion ; and then let them, over and above, examine the other grounds also, which prohibit crowns'nnd indeed all ornament to our heads in par-*- ticulur.⁹ La Cerda adopts a. strange interpretation, making colentes go- vern homines, propria· reliqioniepiq- nora and Deum, and hence dex-iving sanction for the worship of saints (homines) and relies (reliqionie piq- nora), as well as of God.
